<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[145,770,1676,1872]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[146,346,1676,1696]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis (Females):</emphasis>
Head subquadrate; occipital lobe usually present; frontal carina broadly expanded laterad; row of stout setae on base of foretarsus opposite to strigil present; promesonotal suture absent to lightly impressed, never interrupting dorsal mesosomal sculpture; petiolar spiracle facing directly ventrad and sunken within a pit; second gastral (IV abdominal) sternite usually strongly reduced, so that the gaster is directed ventrally and anterad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
